  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "There are several ways you can store app and user data in iCloud. This article describes the various options and their suitability for your app. Each option has trade-offs in complexity, access to iCloud features, and control over how your data persists."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Consider the following approaches before you choose CloudKit."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Store Data as Files",
          "anchor": "3458575"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "If your app stores data as files and you want those files to sync across devices, you can use "
            },
            {
              "type": "emphasis",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "iCloud document storage"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". This storage option gives you granular control over which files to sync. Choosing to store your data as files affords the least control over how your data persists to iCloud, but is relatively simple."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "To use iCloud document storage, use "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsfilemanager/1411653-urlforubiquitycontaineridentifie"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " in "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsfilemanager"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". For more information, see "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "title": "Designing for Documents in iCloud",
              "destination": "https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/General/Conceptual/iCloudDesignGuide/Chapters/DesigningForDocumentsIniCloud.html#//apple_ref/doc/uid/TP40012094-CH2"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "If your files reside on a single device, you can save them using the nonubiquity methods of "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsfilemanager"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". When a user enables "
            },
            {
              "type": "emphasis",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "iCloud Backup"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", a snapshot of these files uploads to iCloud. The user can then restore a device using that snapshot. Note that your app’s data contributes to the overall device backup size. A large total backup size can lead to lengthy restore times. See "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "title": "iCloud Backup",
              "destination": "https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/releasenotes/General/WhatsNewIniOS/Articles/iOS5.html#//apple_ref/doc/uid/TP30915195-SW36"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Store Unstructured Data That Syncs Across Devices",
          "anchor": "3458572"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "If you store a small number of key-value pairs that sync across the user’s devices, you can use "
            },
            {
              "type": "emphasis",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "iCloud key-value storage"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". This approach is simple but doesn’t provide control over how data persists, and it limits the kind of data you can store."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You can store up to 1,024 pairs of string keys to scalar values. The value types supported are "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/swift/bool"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", numeric types, "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/swift/string"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/date"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/data"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/swift/array"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/swift/dictionary"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". You might use this solution to store a user’s preferences or game state as property lists, for example. For more information, see "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsubiquitouskeyvaluestore"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Store Objects That Sync Across Devices",
          "anchor": "3458573"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "If you store your data as objects and relationships, consider using Core Data with CloudKit, or using CloudKit directly. Using CloudKit directly is more complex, but it gives you full control over the data you store, including the design and management of your container’s schema. Use this option if you want direct access to iCloud storage features, such as private data sharing, or if you want to manage local data caching. With a local cache of data, your app can reduce the number of calls to iCloud and can access cached data offline."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "If you only sync private data and you don’t need granular control over which data syncs, you can use "
            },
            {
              "type": "emphasis",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Core Data with CloudKit"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". Core Data with CloudKit stores a local replica of a CloudKit private database and syncs it across all of the user’s devices. This storage option doesn’t support all CloudKit features—for example, it doesn’t support live queries and shared private data—but can be simpler than using CloudKit directly. Core Data with CloudKit manages the schema for your iCloud container, so you don’t have to."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "To get started with CloudKit, see "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/cloudkit/enabling_cloudkit_in_your_app"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". For more information on Core Data with CloudKit, see "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/coredata/mirroring_a_core_data_store_with_cloudkit/setting_up_core_data_with_cloudkit"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
